<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <!--
    Grants access to the macOS *data-protection keychain*, which is the only
    keychain that honors SecAccessControl (the Touch ID / login-password gate
    used by src/secure_store.rs for the auto-unlock key). Without it the app
    silently falls back to the promptless, ungated login Keychain ("keyring"
    tier) — the auto-unlock key then sits on disk readable by any process
    running as the user with no biometric prompt.

    IMPORTANT: on macOS these are *restricted* entitlements. Merely claiming
    them in the signature is NOT enough — the OS ignores them (keychain calls
    return errSecMissingEntitlement, -34018) unless they are ALSO allow-listed
    by an embedded Developer ID *provisioning profile*. CI materializes that
    profile into Contents/embedded.provisionprofile before signing (see
    bundle.macOS.files in tauri.conf.json and .github/workflows/release.yml).
    The profile is generated from an explicit App ID (org.stingle.desktop) with
    the Keychain Sharing capability, and its allow-list must be a superset of
    the entitlements below.

    `application-identifier` is what establishes the app's default keychain
    access group (TEAMID.org.stingle.desktop); without it SecItemAdd on the
    data-protection keychain has no default group and also fails with -34018.

    __TEAM_ID__ is substituted with the real 10-char Apple Team ID at build
    time by .github/workflows/release.yml (from the APPLE_TEAM_ID secret), so
    no team-specific value is committed here.
  -->
  <key>com.apple.application-identifier</key>
  <string>__TEAM_ID__.org.stingle.desktop</string>
  <key>keychain-access-groups</key>
  <array>
    <string>__TEAM_ID__.org.stingle.desktop</string>
  </array>
</dict>
</plist>
